segments.text: This sort of set the groundwork.
We became the official research agency for the Texas Highway Department.
Most of our, well, all of our early funding was from the Texas Highway Department.
That was our only source of funds.
So this started in 1956 when I came.
Now this was the same time that the, or shortly after I got here, later on that fall, they passed the federal
National Congress passed the Highway Revenue Act of 1956, which was the creation of the interstate system, the national system of interstate and defense highways.
As a part of that, they created what they called a research and planning, highway research and planning fund stream off of the special taxations that were set up to fund
The interstate system.
Now, the interstate system was funded from special taxes that were levied $0.05 a gallon against all gasoline, plus taxes on tires and lubricating oils and spare parts.
This went into a trust fund held at the national level.
Out of the trust fund, monies were apportioned
on a formula basis to individual states.
Now, 1.5% of each state's apportionment was eligible for expenditure on planning activities and research.
Now, this really sort of created the research activities in highway transportation.
However, that law said that if those funds were not spent on planning or research activities, they could revert to construction.
And the state could go ahead and use them for construction.
So 1.5% of the income stream to each state off the trust fund was a substantial amount of money.
And it stimulated some.
expansion in the research programs, particularly in areas of materials and what I'd call hard research, bridge work, piers, structural work.
Then as the interstate began to actually go in to get into being in the late 50s,
there became a growing awareness of the social and economic problems that were being created by it.
One of the first early problem areas was the problem of bypassing small towns.
There was a great concern that if the interstate system bypassed a small community, that that community would wither and die.
since it was no longer now had the through traffic to support it.
So that generated a series of studies on the economic consequences of bypasses, and that was some of the earlier work that we did.
And our group then became a department head in TTI over the economics and planning department.
And I believe we had four departments at that time.
And that's not right.
First, Bill Atkins, Dr. William G. Atkins, who is now retired from the system, was head of that group.
And I worked under him.
Then in the late 50s, he left.
to go complete his PhD degree.
And I became head of that group.
And when he completed his PhD, he came back and worked for me then.
We just sort of switched roles.
But in 1964 then, with the Revenue Act of 64, they changed what we call the HPR funding formula, the Highway Planning and Research Fund.

Now the states that did not spend that 1.5% rather than having it available to revert to their construction program where most of them had been using it and very little of it going into planning and research activities, Texas was one of the few states that were using substantial amounts of it.
I said, you either use it or lose it.
If you don't use it for those activities, then it reverts back to the federal government and will become a part of the reapportionment process.
They'll reapportion it to states that do need it.
So that stimulated a substantial new activity in research and planning.
And really, our program grew rather rapidly after 1964.
In the meantime, I had been taking coursework toward a PhD, again in agricultural economics, again under Dr. McNeely.
And I can't even remember when I finished it.
I had to look at the bio data sheet.
I want to say 1965.
I don't think it's right.
It must have been because you're only allowed 10 years to get it done.
Oh, I broke all sorts of rules when I was doing it.
I didn't have a formal program set up until after I'd been taking courses for a long time.
Then I filed a degree plan.
But I also ran into the problem that the university then had a regulation that anyone with a rank greater than assistant professor could not get a
terminal degree here.
Well, I got special dispensation because I had been hired with the proviso that I would be able to do it to complete the degree.
So I'm one of the few people that ever received a degree from A&M carrying the rank of associate.
And it was because I had been
contracted to do that, or it was in our agreement that I would be able to complete a degree.
Well, let me ask you this.
You said that Texas was one of the states that put a lot of money into research on highways.
Is it some of the states that have poorer transportation systems, did they fail to use this research?
For instance, Louisiana and New Mexico, their road systems in those two states
are not up to par with those in Texas for the most part.
Were those two states not using that money for research?
They were not.
In fact, many states were not.
Many states still don't use much of it for research.
It can be used for research or planning.
Now, in recent years, federal planning requirements have gotten ever increasingly stringent, so they've been required to do more and more planning activities.
which have required a greater and greater percentage of the combined research and planning budgets.
So many research budgets that you work on, this doesn't just apply to the interstate center, it applies to all the state highways.
Oh, yeah, right.
No, the funding is just out of that interstate funding stream.
I get the impression from that that probably California was definitely using the money for research and planning.
Texas were?
What were some of the other states that were that you know of?
Oh, Pennsylvania did, New York that had, and Indiana through Purdue.
Most states, now California is an exception, but most states do not have an on-board, a major on-board research capability.
So they do their research through their universities or
consultants or some other way.
California does have its own in-house research program.
Now, Texas doesn't have much of one.
We and the University of Texas do most of theirs.
They do a little bit, but, oh, 10% of what we do.
I thought this TTI was meeting that requirement that you said there.
It is.
Now, back in 19...

late 50s and I'm not sure just what time we developed what we call the cooperative research program with the highway department that means and this is a unique arrangement among state departments and universities and that we're the only one that really has this sort of an arrangement the University of Texas then
came into it in about 1968.
They also developed the same sort of agreement with the University of Texas.
But this is a system whereby we jointly get together with the department and with their district engineers and determine what sorts of research needs to be done in the coming year.
And in the spring of the year, we formulate a research program to begin in September
in the beginning of the new fiscal year.

And we have an agreement with the department that we will try to keep this in a sort of a constant mode in terms of total amount of money available for research so that we can plan for it and get the people and keep them and but that we will jointly determine through a series of area research committees.
There are four of them in the department has that we
work with those area committees in areas or areas of materials and pavements and structures and economics and planning.
We work with those to develop the research program for the coming year.
And we have a strong input into what sorts of research is going to be done.
So we and the University of Texas, and they operate the same way now,
do the research for the Texas Highway Department, for the State Department of Highways and Public Transportation in the state.
Now, in addition, we do, of course, this year, for example, that'll be about $1.6 million that we will do in our cooperative research program with the Highway Department.
But now, in addition, for the last 10 or 15 years,
We do direct contract work with the federal government, with other states, with other state agencies, with trade associations, and with private industry.
So the co-op program, the program of the highway department, which originally was our total program, now this year we'll have about, the year we're in now,
about $7.2 million worth of research, of which the states will be about in our cooperative about 1.6.
So it's a very, very important part of our research activity, in that it is the one program which we have, which allows us continuity.
But in terms of total
it's only about less than 25% of our program.
About how many researchers do you have employed at TTI?
Are the faculty members working half-time or what?
We have both.
We have a total of, gosh, the numbers again get me.
We have a total of about 125.
FTEs, full-time equivalent, professionals.
Now, we have 327 people, but now that includes all of our technicians, our clerical, secretarial.
We have a large technical group at the research annex.
All the students and graduate students that we use in the research program.
So the total body count is going to be well over 300.
But in terms of professional full-time equivalents, we have about 125, 127.
Where are all of the facilities used in the research, where are they located?
OK. On campus, right in this complex primarily.
Here, back in the asphalt lab, the concrete labs.
Those are campus activities.
They're concentrated here.
Now, we've got people scattered in other places.
But here on campus, out at the research annex, we have our safety division headquartered there.
In the Hirschfield properties in Austin, we have our accident analysis division headquartered there.
What properties is that?
This is the Joe Moore, the Hirschfield estate that Joe Moore from the A&M Development Foundation bought and remodeled, spent about a million dollars remodeling the thing.
How do you spell that, Hirschfield?
H-I-R-S-C-H-F-I-E-L-D. And he wanted someone from A&M to be in the properties, and so we had been in commercial lease space in Austin.
And so we moved in January from that space over to the Hirschfield properties because he wanted someone there, and it's very nice and very convenient.
But we have an office in Austin.
We have one in Dallas.
We have one in Houston, one in San Antonio, one in Arkansas, plus the campus and out at the research annex.
Now, you were asking about joint employees.
I've got 120 some odd.
The last count I had, we had 37 of those people were jointly employed with academic communities, academic departments, primarily with the civil engineering department.
That's our largest single one.
But we have people with the joint employees with the Department of Economics, the Sociology, Institute of Statistics, of course,
practically all of the engineering departments, chemical engineering, industrial, mechanical, geology.
But we have a number of joint.

And that's really one of the functions of the Institute is to be able to provide the mechanism where we can, if we need expertise that's in an academic department, there's a mechanism of how we can bring them aboard and let them participate in the research programs.
Do you consider the level of funding that the agency receives by the state to be adequate?
Nobody ever gets adequate funding from the state.
We do not get a great deal of state general revenue funds, and traditionally have not.
Of our budget this year, only less than 10% of our budget will be state general revenue funds.
And the other 90% is soft money.
That is money that we acquire through contracts.
Now, that is not enough to sustain an operation over time.
That's one of the objectives going through our target 2000 and our five-year planning process.
One of our objectives is to increase the proportion of state general revenue funds
available to the Institute to the 20 to 25% range.

So that and for a number of reasons, not just in order to have the money available, but one of the things that a research organization should do is to identify emerging problem areas before those problems become critical to
look at problems that are not the domain of any one funding agency.
Lots of problems never get addressed because no one has direct responsibility for that problem area.
So we need, we feel, to have state general revenue funds sufficient to enable us to, one, bring in people with expertise
in areas that we do not now have funded research projects to support them on, and let them develop research in those areas, the seed money concept.
Secondly, to allow us to conduct a modest amount of research in those areas where no one is now responsible for that problem, so that problem does not get addressed, the intermodal

problems for example no one either at the federal level or at the state level is responsible for the interact interactions between let's say railroads and trucking or airports and good movements the truck and rail industry supply and airports the interactions of those or the problems of
piggyback operations, truck rail operations.
So there's lots of problem areas that do not get addressed because in the governmental frameworks that divide the responsibilities, they fall through the cracks.
So there needs to be resources available to allow you to do those, to do policy studies, which no one really has responsibility for, to answer questions that
no one really has the prerogative to ask in a modal agency.
For example, what should be the state's role or the state's posture toward transportation development?
No one at the state has
the prerogative to fund research to answer that question.
Since the state does not have a role in transportation, it has a highway system with its own requirements, an aeronautics commission with its purviews over air, a Texas Railroad Commission.
It has a water system that nobody really has any responsibilities for, and a pipeline system that has nobody to ask questions about it.
But the state does not have a mechanism by which it can look at what should be the transportation balance.
Where should we be trying to influence transportation growth, transportation development area?
What should the state's posture be with regard to conflicts between modes of transportation?
The pipeline railroad conflict on cold slurry pipelines, for example.
So, you know, somebody needs to be in a position to look at some of those problems.
What has TTI done to promote highway safety?
Highway safety has been one of the large things that we've been operating and working on.
And you're always...
subject to omission when you start listing the things that you've done in the past, but there are some very visible things that we have done.
We developed very early what we called the forgiving roadway concept.
Now this is sort of analogous to the
old military expression that if it moves, salute it.
If it doesn't move, pick it up.
If you can't pick it up, paint it.
Well, we took that sort of an attitude toward highway roadways, and we said if it doesn't need to be there, move it.
Clear the roadway to the extent you can.
If you can't clear it, then protect it.
If you can't protect it, then make it break away.
So with that, we started out and we were the ones that developed the breakaway signs.
All of the large, and this primarily was developed for interstate systems, where they had the big, massive sign boards because of high speed.
and the massive sign frame that those things had to support.
Well, you had the big H beams that were the supports.
Well, these were lethal.
If you ran off the road and hit one of those, it was bad news all the way around.
So one of the early research activities we had in the late 60s, I believe about 68, was the development of a breakaway concept to make those signs break away.
Now, the last estimate that I saw was, I don't remember the numbers, but up in literally the tens of thousands of lives that have been saved by making those signs break away.
Multi-billions of dollars of value in terms of property loss and loss of life saved through those systems.
From that, we went to the breakaway of the luminary supports, light poles, and that was a major...
uh, safety breakthrough.
And then, uh, that took care of the part of those things that you had to leave there and you could do something about to make them less dangerous.
And then we developed a, uh, what is now known as the Texas crash cushion, the impact attenuation systems, the barrel systems, uh, for those areas like, uh, parapets, bridge radio, uh, bridge piers,
Gore areas that have concrete walls that if you want to turn off on an exit ramp, for example, and you don't make your decision quick enough and try to turn and don't make it, you hit the wall.
And one place on 59 in Houston, they had like 13 deaths in just a matter of months of people hitting a parapet wall.
So we developed the crash cushions, and those are now in use nationwide.
Dr. Hirsch and Dr. Ivey and Dr. Olson were all instrumental in developing both the breakaway signs, breakaway light poles, and the
and the crash cushions.
Now, that's one concept, or that's one area of the safety, in the hardware area.
We have ongoing programs in developing bridge ratings.
We also developed the Texas twist, for example, on guardrails.
One of the big problems in roadside safety was you put up a guardrail, and sometimes the guardrail becomes more dangerous than what you were trying to protect them from.
and if you were to go off the road, particularly in the old guardrail system where you just stubbed out the end and it sat there.
And you've probably seen the gory pictures where somebody hit that head on and the guardrail comes through the car and through the occupant and out the back end.
So we developed a safe end treatment for guardrails.
Again, that's on the hardware system.
One of the big problems that we've addressed and now have a solution to is the problem of restraining heavy vehicles on bridges and overpasses.
You may recall a couple of years ago the big ammonia truck accident in Houston where the ammonia truck was coming around
over one of the overpasses and ran through the guardrail, went down two levels below, and it hit and ruptured and killed either eight or ten people and injured like 110.
They closed the interchanges up.
So this focused attention on the need to develop a system, a guardrail system or a bridge rating system that could be used in especially sensitive areas like that.
to restrain those heavy vehicles.

They had the Martinez, California school bus incident when 27 school children were killed because a bus went through a guardrail again on an overpass and went down several 20, 30 feet and killed a whole bunch of kids.
So those are what I would call safety hardware sort of things.
the national leaders in the development of those for the last 15, 20 years.

At the same time, we've been doing some very good work in hydroplaning and trying to assure that the vehicle-roadway interaction is, it's not a good term, but to assure that we're building, using the right materials to
to provide skid resistance that's necessary to keep the vehicle on the roadway.
So we've done hydroplaning work.
We've developed new materials for lightweight aggregate or surface treatments to give you high coefficient of friction so that you can retain the control of the car.
This is all a wet weather problem, by the way.
You don't have the problem in dry weather.
It's when you get rain.
You get a buildup of water.
Now, this buildup is just a film.
It can be just a film.

But if you have, under the worst conditions, a very slick pavement, that is a very smooth pavement, and smooth tires, and low tire pressure, and high speed, you can hydroplane or get riding up on that film of water and totally lose contact between the tire and the pavement.
So you try to turn the wheel, and nothing happens.
Or you may go into just a total spin.
So we've been developing materials and roadway systems to minimize hydroplaning, to minimize the adverse effects of wet weather.
Do you conduct your highway crash tests here?
Add it to Research Annex.
Let me ask you this.
Do you know how Texas ranks the other states?
No, I really don't.
I'm sure those... We had one place where Nevada, I believe, had the highest fatality rate on its highways.
Maybe it was Wyoming, one of the western states.
Yeah, it was one of the western states, and I sort of believe it was Wyoming.
I believe it was.
They also have the lowest compliance rate with the 55-mile-an-hour speed limit, I think.
But they've got some special problems.
They've got ice problems and all of that to deal with.
I'm sure those numbers, those rankings are available in terms of...
Vehicle miles traveled, deaths per vehicle miles traveled by state.
But I really don't know just how we rank.
I would say that Texas, or I would think that Texas would rank fairly good.
Now, we are not a state that believes in low speeds.
Our compliance with the 55-mile-an-hour speed limit is not as bad as Wyoming's, but we're not in compliance either.
Our people don't drive 55 miles an hour, as you well know if you're out on Interstate 45 somewhere.
If you drive 55, everybody's passing you.
But it is better than it was.
And in the areas where speed is a critical safety problem,
I think we're doing better than we are in areas where it's not, like on the interstate system.
Speed is not really that big a safety problem on the interstate, because it was designed for it.
Where speed's a real problem is on the foreign market roads in the rural system, where it was designed, you know, 40-mile turns, and you'd go 45, and you'd be in a ditch.
That's where we're really speed-sensitive in terms of accident rates.
Do you have any idea on how the state police are enforcing the 55 mile per hour speed?
Writing tickets just fast as they can.
Again, the numbers are not, I won't swear to the numbers, but if I recall correctly, their numbers of tickets issued last year was like 1,800,000 tickets.
they have increased in each of the last several years like 25% or 30% each year in the number of tickets they have issued.
Are most of these tickets being issued on interstate or on the farm and market roads or on just regular state highways?
I would guess that most, well, I don't know for sure, but I would say that a good portion of them are on the interstate and on the major U.S. highways, which carry most of the traffic.
they're going to concentrate their activities on those areas where they've got most of the vehicles.
In view of the large size of the state of Texas, how does it happen to have one of the better highway systems in the nation?
Several reasons.
One, it has always had a very well-managed,
and very honest highway department.
Now this has not been true in many of the other states.
It's had a highway department, or state department of highways and public transportation now, which has been free of scandal since the Mall Ferguson days.
That was the last period in which there was a political
influence in the Highway Department.
It has been... That was in what year approximately?
Mid-20s?
Yeah, the Maul Paul Ferguson governorship era where there was some highway scandals back in those areas, but the Highway Department has been relatively free of political influence.
It has been a very well managed, very professionally operated department, which means that with the money available they
put it to good use.
How do you think the political influence was less in Texas than it was in other states?
Why was this?
I really don't know.
As I say, during the Ma Ferguson era, we had it here.
Gosh, they've got it in all other states now, or not all other states.
They've got it in several other states now.
bid rigging, kickback, Spiro Agnew.
What are some of the states where this occurs?
Oh, Maryland was one.
Spiro Agnew was up to his ears in it.
In fact, didn't he get sent to jail over the kickbacks?
I think he did.
For not reporting the income, I believe.
I believe it was from actually taking the kickback.
It was from not reporting it.
Pennsylvania's got it right now.
or have had it, they're just now cleaning theirs up.
Massachusetts, Tennessee has had it up to their ears.
Many states, for example, Texas, being apolitical, has had a very stable highway department.
Take Pennsylvania, for example, before the current commissioner, who's a good friend of mine, Tom Larson, took over.
They turned over their whole personnel every time they changed, and they were in a bipartisan,
area, so when the Democrats got in, they wiped out the whole department.
They were under civil service agreements.
No, no.
And they started all over again, so it became a part of the patronage process, the highway department jobs, and it's reflected.
Now, in addition to good management and lack of political influence on the department, these are my opinions, of course, and good leadership, but C. Greer and the highway...
He's still on the highway, Gordon.
No, he just stepped down a matter of months ago.
But Mr. Luther Deberry, who's the one that just has been stepped down about a year ago, and Mark Good now has it, but they've all been high-quality professional people.
Now, in addition, I've got to put in a plug for the
continuing long-term research programs that they have funded.
Texas has been a leader in the development of new materials, of new design, of new traffic systems.
They have not only funded the research, but through this integration of the research with the department, they've used it.
That and...
A large area of the state is very favorably situated from the standpoint of soil and climate for rope building.
Now, a lot of it is very miserably suited, too, but a bigger section of it is good than is bad.
The bad part is around the Gulf Coast.
Gulf Coast, Beaumont area, and we're in a bad area here with the Taylor Marl.
It's a heaving soil problem.
that runs all the way up Corsicana, that area.
What was that?
Taylor what?
Marl, M-A-R-L.
It's a soil type.
Very fine-grained clays that absorb water and expand when they're wet massively, and then when they dry, they contract massively, and it's a heaving soil problem.
Very difficult.
My house, I can't close a door in it.
I keep
cleaning off the doors because the soil keeps expanding and contracting.
So this is a bad area.
But you get out in West Texas, and that's great road building country.
That and the fact that, well, I guess those are the major things that I would say.
In closing, could you tell me,
A little bit more about the research projects that have recently been completed, some that you may not have touched on, or some that are underway now that are significant.
Let me run through probably two or three different things that I think that we have underway that are currently answering real problems.
One of the things that greatly concerns everyone in the highway industry is the tremendous
Susceptibility of the road building industry to the oil problem, particularly the concerns over foreign oil.
Asphalt, which is the major binder for use in roadway building, is of course a derivative of petroleum.
It comes from crude oil and is the residual from the refining process, or one of the residuals.
As in a period of real oil shortage, the refining process will squeeze that residual even down, so it'll shorten the amount of asphalt available.
Even greater, perhaps, than the amount of gasoline that's produced, because they can make refining changes that will reduce the percentage of asphalt out of a given barrel of oil.
not into gasoline, but into home heating oils and other things like that that use the heavy end as well.
Asphalt prices have gone from, say, pre-'74, they were less than $20 a ton, to around $200 a ton now.
So they have become very expensive.
So it is very important that we try to develop
substitutes for asphalt, which we're working on now.

One of the most abundant elements, and particularly as we go into the EPA requirements to reduce pollution and continue to develop sour crude and sour gas areas, is the production of abatement sulfur.
We have research projects underway to attempt to utilize sulfur as either a partial replacement for asphalt as a binder or a total replacement.
Now these are two different concepts.
The partial replacement is what we, and there are two different processes.
The Shell Canada process and a French process which they call the d'Aquitaine process.
process.
I wish I could.
It's an individual's name, and I think it's D-A-C-Q-U-A-T-A-I-N, the Aquitaine process.
Anyway, these two processes are ways of homogenizing
liquid asphalt heated and liquid heated sulfur to extend through substituting sulfur for asphalt to provide a binder up to, say, 30% or 40% of the asphalt can be substituted with sulfur.
And it actually provides perhaps a better.
We haven't finished the evaluations over time yet.
But it looks very, very promising to where you can replace with another material some of this asphalt.
Now the other process, and we're entering into the second contract now to evaluate its effectiveness, is what we call plasticized sulfur.
And that's just taking sulfur, molten liquid sulfur, and adding plasticizers to it to change its character so that you can make a flexible pavement binder of it.
And that looks very promising.
The problem being right now, not with the sulfur, but with the cost of the plasticizers that you have to add to it to make it act like a flexible binder.
But these are areas where we're trying to develop new materials to replace things that we know are going to get increasingly scarce, increasingly expensive, and increasingly sensitive to
other market activities where we, you know, we may hit a time when for periods of time there just won't be any asphalt or will be only a half enough to do the road building.
So we've got to do something.
Where is Texas getting most of its asphalt now?
Of course, we're getting it from the refineries in Texas here.
There are a number of major asphalt producers, major refineries that
They produce it as a normal part of the refining process.
But that one is in the materials area.
Another very important area, and one that gets overlooked a lot, is we have quit building highways.
Now, we haven't really quit.
But we're not adding freeways or expressways in Houston, for example, nearly at the rate
at which we're adding vehicles and vehicle miles of travel.
So as a little over-exaggeration, we have quit several years ago building facilities.
Now we're going in and trying to repair and update and modify existing facilities.
Many of those have hit their life expectancy, and they've got to be redone.
So we're putting our money in that, in the maintenance and rehabilitation of our existing plant, rather than adding to the plant.
At the same time, the demand placed on those facilities is increasing each year.
For example, Houston, the last time I looked, was adding a net to their vehicle fleet, this is Harris County, of 400 vehicles a day.
Every day, 400 more vehicles than there was the day before to accommodate on that set amount of facility.
Well, the problem is you've got all of the growing demand.
You don't have any increased supply.
So how do you make what you have there work more efficiently and more effectively to stretch the supply, as it were, or to accommodate a part of the increased demand?
It's a losing game, but it's a fighting of a delaying action until you can come up with a better solution.
So our research has been geared very strongly, particularly in areas like Houston and Dallas, to how do you modify existing facilities to squeeze more capacity out of them?
How do you accommodate other people movement as opposed to vehicle movement on existing facilities?
And we're doing some of that through our big van pooling program, our occupancy vehicle lane,
program on new freeways.
We've got one of those coming in on Gulf Freeway in Houston, for example.
The contra flow lane that we've got on I-45 coming out now.
Have you been through that?
It's on I-45 coming out of downtown Houston up toward Conroe.
In the morning, in the morning, we take
one of the outbound lanes, the one coming north, and convert it into an inbound lane.

And then in the afternoon, we switch over on the other side of the median, add one of the inbound lanes now going south over to the outbound lane coming north, and use that for buses and van pools and high occupancy vehicles.
We're getting more capacity out of the system by doing that.
It's expensive in that it costs you.
You've got to go down and set it up every morning and take it down every morning and then set it up and take it down every afternoon.
But so far it's been safe and has increased the capacity of those systems.
So those are some of the types of things that we think are critical to us.
We're going to have to make a better use of what we have now.
At the same time, we have got to come up with new solutions to the problems that we've been facing for 30 years that have grown more and more acute and yet have never been solved.
And we have plenty of problems to work on for the rest of my lifetime in transportation.
Thank you, Dr. Wood, for taking the time to talk with me.
You've been most helpful.
I appreciate it and enjoyed it.
